##Application Layer - HTTP

Application layer uses two architectures: 
1. Client-server architecture(centralized)
2. Peer-to-peer architecture(decentralized)

Key points to remember:
1. Webpage has objects
2. Each object has a URL
3. All objects stay at the base HTML file
4. URL : Uniform Resource Locator
5. Browsers use port 80

Types of HTTP:
1. Non-persistent HTTP: For each object, TCP/IP connection is set up once, and then ended 
2. Persistent HTTP: All objects are transferred within one TCP/IP connection

RTT: Round Trip time
FTT: File Transmission Time

Non-persistent HTTP Response time = 2*RTT + FTT
Persistent HTTP response time = 2* num of obj +FTT

Caching:
Average response time = LAN Delay + Access Delay + Internet Delay

Stale cache: Cache memory that is not updated ans different from the root servers version

## Application Layer : Email and DNS

SMTP: Push methodology
HTTP, POP3, IMAP: Pull methodology

SMTP -> Simple Mail Transfer Protocol, uses port 25
SMTP has 3 phases-
1. Handshaking
2. Transfer of messages, messages are 7 bit ASCII
3. Closure

POP -> Post Office Protocol, uses port 110
IMAP -> Internet Mail Access Protocol

Key facts:
1. DNS servers distribute load through a round robin method
2. TLD(Top level domains): com, edu, org
3. DNS queries can be two types - Iterated query and recursive query


##DNS records:
RR format: (name, value, type, ttl)

type=A : Name is hostname, value is IP
type=CNAME : Name is alias name, value is canonical name
type=NS : Name is domain, value is hostname of authoritative name server of the domain
type=MX : Value is name of mail server associated with name

##Application layer: FTP, P2P and CDN

CDN = Content Distribution Network

Two types of encoding used in video streaming-
1. Spatial encoding
2. Temporal encoding

CBR: Constant Bit rate
VBR: Variable Bit rate

Streaming: DASH

DASH stands for Dynamic, Adaptive streaming over HTTP

CDN uses either Enter Deep or Bring Home method to distribute content globally 

